sec.p:
Lead halide perovskite solar cells have drawn enormous attention due to their rapid rise in device power conversion efficiency (PCE), only within a few years, now hitting a record PCE of 22 % achieved by Seok’s group (KRICT/UNIST, South Korea), although the device was not stabilized [1]. The perovskite crystal structure has the chemical formula of ABX3, where in the perovskite molecule used in solar cells as the light-harvesting layer, A is usually methylammonium, B is lead, and X is a halogen or a mixture of several halogens, thus making the CH3NH3PbX3 molecule with proper light absorbance and bandgap suitable for photovoltaic applications [2, 3]. Miyasaka was the first who employed it as a sensitizer layer in dye-sensitized solar cells and achieved a PCE of 3.8 % [4]. Since then, attempts have been made to engineer the device structure to increase the efficiency and stability [5]. Methylammonium lead halide perovskite usually forms according to the following chemical reaction between its two precursors:1PbX2+CH3NH3X→Organicsolvents,Temp.CH3NH3PbX3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
